  <static seed="523" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/IdentifyAxisVertex60.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the axis of symmetry and vertex of the quadratic function.</p>
<p><m>{y}={3+4x-x^{2}}</m></p>
<p>Axis of symmetry: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p>Vertex: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x = 2</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(2,7\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This quadratic function is not in standard form. We need to re-order it into standard form:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{y}={-x^{2}+4x+3}}</m></p>
<p>Now we can identify that:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ a=-1,b=4,c=3 }</m></p>
<p>To find the parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry, we use the formula <m>\displaystyle{x=-\frac{b}{2a}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
  x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \\
   \amp = -\frac{4}{2(-1)} \\
   \amp = 2
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s axis is <m>\displaystyle{x=2}</m>.</p>
<p>Next we substitute <m>\displaystyle{x=2}</m> into <m>\displaystyle{{y}={-x^{2}+4x+3}}</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = -1(2)^{2}+4(2)+3 \\
    \amp = -1 \cdot 4 + 8 + 3 \\
    \amp = {7}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s vertex is <m>\displaystyle{(2,{7})}</m>.</p>
</solution>
